Reference-contexts: Visual Basic implements a shared Data Structure interapplication communication method, Dynamic Data Exchange (DDE). DDE communicates to the other applications what information to put into, or take out of, the clipboard ( a shared memory). The method in which DDE works <ref> [VB 4] </ref> is that one Windows application (called the client) tells another Windows application (called the server) that it requires information. <p> A cold link means that the client must explicitly request updates. A notification link is one in which the server tells the client that data has changed, but it would not be written to the shared memory until the client requests it. Object Linking and Embedding (OLE) <ref> [VB 4] </ref> is also implemented in Visual Basic. It originally was a technology that complimented and extended DDE by allowing applications to link to a common object which resides on a shared memory (create a reference to the shared object).
